{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"a04dacf0-e433-40ea-8cc2-2d39a0b9e852","content":"Run **`dotnet workload update`**. Here's why:\n\n- **`dotnet workload update`** — downloads and installs the **latest versions** of all installed workloads to match your current SDK. After an SDK update, this is exactly what you need to bring workloads (like `maui`) in sync.\n\n- **`dotnet workload repair`** — **reinstalls** the workloads you already have *at their current versions*. It fixes corrupted or incomplete installations but doesn't upgrade anything.\n\nSince your SDK moved forward but your workloads didn't, `update` is the right choice:\n\n```bash\ndotnet workload update\n```\n\nIf builds still fail after that, verify the MAUI workload is installed:\n\n```bash\ndotnet workload list\n```","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"0ae4ecb3-9b00-45bb-9553-c5af400b4077","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about the difference between `dotnet workload update` and `dotnet workload repair` to fix build issues after a .NET SDK update. This is a general knowledge question — I don't need to explore any codebase.","outputTokens":249,"requestId":"1017:92DE6:1587412:1819DA4:69FD33B1"},"id":"cc1f89d1-050f-49b2-8b9e-42e66149b949","timestamp":"2026-05-08T00:52:09.110Z","parentId":"1aafed96-5bbc-4b6c-b48f-df618f79803d"}
